Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns from the Thread.Abort migration guide:

| Pattern | Location | API |
|---|---|---|
| **ASP.NET request termination** | `btnExport_Click` | `Response.End()` |
| **ASP.NET request termination** | `btnRedirect_Click` | `Response.Redirect(url, true)` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `btnRedirect_Click` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` |

## Migrated ASP.NET Core Controller (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Response.End() → return FileContentResult; no abort needed.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // Response.Redirect(url, true) → return RedirectResult.
    // ThreadAbortException catch block → removed entirely.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| .NET Framework | ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.Clear/Write/End` | `return File(bytes, ...)` | MVC returns results; the framework writes the response. `Response.End()` threw `ThreadAbortException` internally — that API doesn't exist. |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Handled by `FileContentResult` | The `File()` helper sets `Content-Disposition` automatically. |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | The `true` (endResponse) parameter called `Thread.Abort` to stop execution. In Core, just `return` — execution stops naturally. |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Removed** | This catch only existed because `Redirect(url, true)` threw it. With `return Redirect(...)`, no exception is thrown. |
| `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` | `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` | In Core, `Identity` can be null. Use null-conditional access. |
| WebForms event handlers | `[HttpPost]` action methods | WebForms doesn't exist in Core. Controller actions return `IActionResult`. |

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Don't write to `Response.Body` then return an `IActionResult`** — pick one. The `File()` helper handles everything.
2. **Don't catch `OperationCanceledException` as a replacement for `ThreadAbortException`** — in this case, the catch was only needed because of `Thread.Abort`. Remove it entirely.
3. **`User.Identity` can be null in Core** — always use `?.` or you'll get `NullReferenceException` in unauthenticated scenarios.
4. **For long-running report generation**, accept `CancellationToken` from `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:
   ```csharp
   public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken ct)
   {
       var data = await GenerateReportAsync(ct);
       return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
   }
   ```
   This lets the framework cancel work if the client disconnects — the cooperative replacement for the old preemptive abort model.
